You are working on a full-stack project consisting of three parts:
- jfs_application (C:\MobAPP\JFS\jfs_application) — client mobile app on Flutter/Dart.
- yfs_app_staff (C:\MobAPP\YFS-staff\yfs_app_staff) — staff mobile app on Flutter/Dart.
- YFS (C:\Users\owlni\PhpstormProjects\YFS) — admin panel and API on Laravel (PHP). Contains the database; both mobile apps communicate with it via REST API.

Domain context:
- Client and Staff are now split into two independent Flutter applications.
- The Staff application is used to administer a children's fashion show by scanning each child's QR code at every stage checkpoint.
- The YFS admin panel is built with Laravel + Filament and is used by administrators to configure and manage the event data and workflow.
- Both Flutter applications and Laravel/Filament must stay aligned through API contracts.

General:
- Prefer small, reviewable diffs.
- Never change unrelated files.
- Preserve existing architecture and naming unless asked.
- If you add a dependency, update pubspec.yaml (Flutter) or composer.json (Laravel) and explain why.
- When working on an API endpoint, keep both Flutter apps and Laravel consistent (request/response format, route names, etc.).

Flutter/Dart (jfs_application and yfs_app_staff):
- Use null-safety.
- Prefer const constructors where possible.
- Use Flutter lints and keep analysis clean.
- Avoid breaking widget rebuild performance; keep build() pure.

Laravel/PHP (YFS):
- Follow PSR-12 coding style.
- Use Eloquent models and Laravel conventions (Form Requests, Resources, etc.).
- Keep migrations and seeders up to date when changing DB schema.

State management (Flutter):
- Do not introduce a new state management library unless requested.
- If an existing approach is present (Provider/Riverpod/BLoC/setState), follow it.

Code quality:
- Add/adjust tests when changing logic (unit/widget tests for Flutter, PHPUnit for Laravel if the project has them).
- Keep formatting with dart format (Flutter) and pint/php-cs-fixer (Laravel).

When asked to implement features:
- First propose a short plan.
- Then implement with minimal changes.

